load("movies.Rdata")

Part 1: Data

Can we understand what will be popular with audiences by looking at movie features? We’ll try to answer this question with a random sample of 651 movies produced and released before 2016, originally sourced through the Rottentomatoes and IMDB API. Specifically, we’ll apply Bayesian Regression techniques to predict the audience score from the data. Since the data is a random sample, we expect the results to be generalizable but we cannot make causal statements due to the lack of random assignment.

Thankfully the data is very clean, with no missing values in audience_score.

Our rubric tells us to create some new variables:

  • feature_film: yes if the movie is a feature film, no otherwise
  • drama: yes if the movie is in the drama genre, no otherwise
  • mpaa_rating_R: yes if the movie is R-rated, no otherwise
  • oscar_season: yes if the movie was released during the so-called ‘oscar season’ from October through December
  • summer_season: yes if the movie was released in the summer months

We’ll leverage dplyr’s mutate function to create these all at once and store them in a new dataframe movies_clean

movies_clean <- movies %>%
  mutate(
    feature_film = ifelse(title_type == "Feature Film", "yes", "no"),
    drama = ifelse(genre == "Drama", "yes", "no"),
    mpaa_rating_R = ifelse(mpaa_rating == "R", "yes", "no"),
    oscar_season = ifelse(thtr_rel_month >= 10, "yes", "no"),
    summer_season = ifelse(thtr_rel_month %in% c(5,6,7,8), "yes", "no")
  )

Part 3: Exploratory data analysis

First, since we’re looking to predict our audience_score data, we should take a look at the distribution and see if anything odd jumps out at us.

x = round(mean(movies_clean$audience_score),1)
movies_clean %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = audience_score)) +
  geom_density() +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept=mean(audience_score)), color="blue", linetype="dashed", size=1) +
  labs(title = "Distribution of Audience Scores",
       subtitle = paste("n = ",length(movies_clean$audience_score),", ", "Mean = ", x))

We see the distribution is left-skewed, with a peak around 80-85.

movies_clean %>%

We can see some interesting things in the boxplots for Feature Films and Dramas vs Audience Score from our sample. It appears that non-feature films have a higher median audience score than feature films, and dramas have higher median scores than non-dramas. Movies released in oscar season have a slightly higher median score than movies outside of oscar season. R-rating and movies released during the summer season don’t appear to have much of a difference in scores.

Part 4: Modeling

Next, we’ll create a Bayesian regression model to predict audience_score as a function of our explanatory variables. Per the rubric we already have the variables pre-selected for us, so as a first pass we’ll use OLS to explore a model with all of the required variables:

movies_subset <- movies_clean %>%
  select(feature_film, drama, runtime, mpaa_rating_R, thtr_rel_year, oscar_season, summer_season, imdb_rating, imdb_num_votes,
         critics_score, best_pic_nom, best_pic_win, best_actor_win, best_actress_win, best_dir_win, top200_box, audience_score)
m_audience <- lm(audience_score ~ . , data = movies_subset)
summary(m_audience)

So it looks like imdb_rating, critics_score, and runtime would be our most predictive features here, with thtr_rel_year and best_pic_nomyes sitting at the borderline of significance (under the frequentist interpretation).

We should also check the residuals to see if they align with our assumption that the residuals are normally distributed with mean 0:

m_audience_aug <- augment(m_audience)
m_audience_aug %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=.fitted, y=.resid)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.6) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed") +
  labs(x = "Fitted Values", y = "Residuals", title = "Linearity and Constant Variance Check of the Residuals")

m_audience_aug %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_qq(aes(sample = .std.resid)) +
  geom_abline(slope = 1, intercept = 0, linetype = "dashed") +
  labs(x = "Theoretical quantiles", y = "Standardized Residuals", title = "Normality Plot of the Residuals")

And we see that the assumption of normality holds.

Next we’ll use the BAS package to implement Bayesian model averaging (BMA). We’ll use a non-informative reference prior BIC for the prior distribution of the coefficients and a uniform distribution for the prior probability of each model.

bma_audience = bas.lm(audience_score ~ ., data = movies_subset,
                 prior = "BIC", modelprior = uniform())

The summary gives us the Bayes Factors and posterior probabilities of the top 5 models. The model with the highest posterior probability uses (in addition to the intercept) runtime, imdb_rating, and critics_score, while the second best model uses imdb_rating and critics_score only. Interestingly enough - the features that we created earlier are not included in any of these models. This also seems to jive with the top features in the OLS model, which is a little comforting.

Model 1 and Model 2 each account for about 13% of the posterior probability, which is pretty large considering that there were 2^16 potential models that were assigned a uniform prior probability.

We should also examine the distribution of the coefficients. For brevity, we’ll just look at the ones that were included in any of the top 5 models: runtime, mpaa_rating_R, imdb_rating, critics_score, and best_actor_winyes.

coef_bma_audience <- coef(bma_audience)
par(mfrow = c(3, 2), col.lab = "darkgrey", col.axis = "darkgrey", col = "darkgrey")
plot(coef_bma_audience, subset=c(4,5,9,11,14), ask=FALSE)

And we see that the coefficients are normally distributed except for imdb_rating.

For the prediction, we’ll use a subset of the data with just runtime, imdb_rating, critics_score, mpaa_rating_R, and best_actor_win to predict audience_score.

movies_red <- movies_clean %>%
  select(runtime, imdb_rating, critics_score, mpaa_rating_R, best_actor_win, audience_score)

Our reduced model will use BMA with the non-informative prior on the regression coefficients.

bma_audience_red <- bas.lm(audience_score ~ ., data = movies_red, prior = "BIC", modelprior = uniform())

Part 5: Prediction

We can then predict the audience_score from a movie released after 2016 (i.e. isn’t in the training set). I liked “Thor: Ragnarok”, so let’s pull down the data (manually) into a dataframe thor_data.

runtime = from Rottentomatoes, 130 minutes imdb_rating = from imdb, 7.9 critics_score = from Rottentomatoes, 93% mpaa_rating_R = from imdb, no best_actor_win = from imdb, yes. Sir Anthony Hopkins won Best Actor for Silence of the Lambs in 1992.

thor_data <- data.frame(
  runtime = 130,
  imdb_rating = 7.9,
  critics_score = 93,
  mpaa_rating_R = "no",
  best_actor_win = "yes"
)

We’ll use simulation in BAS to build our predictive model, using the BMA estimator.

BMA_pred_audience <- predict(bma_audience_red, estimator = "BMA", se.fit = TRUE, newdata = thor_data)
ci_bma_audience <- confint(BMA_pred_audience, estimator = "BMA")
opt_bma <- which.max(BMA_pred_audience$fit)
ci_bma_audience[opt_bma, ]
##      2.5%     97.5%      pred 
##  65.31758 104.84639  85.00447

And the resulting prediction is that the audience score from Rottentomatoes would be 85, with a 95% probability that it would be between 64.95 and 104.86. The actual audience score was 87 - that’s pretty great!

Part 6: Conclusion

So using Bayesian Multiple Linear Regression, we were able to create a predictive model of the Rottentomatoes audience score given 5 different features of the movie with a 95% credible interval. We found that the most predictive features were the runtime, IMDB rating, critics’ score on Rottentomatoes, and whether or not the movie had an R rating and whether or not the movie had a leading actor who had previously won an Oscar for best actor/actress. However, this model incorporates information such as critics’ score and IMDB rating - features that would only be known after the movie has been released (or shortly before). So if we wanted to predict future movie success on an unreleased movie, we would only be able to predict audience score using the information that we have at the time (i.e. R rating, runtime, oscar winning actors).
